                <p><strong>Bishnupur</strong></p>
                <p>Bishnupur is the temple town of Bankura. Patronised under the Malla rulers who rules for a thousand years, Bishnupur grew as the principal centres of culture in Bengal.  Exquisite terracotta temples built in the 16th – 17th century adorn the town which brought Bishnupur in the UNESCO World Heritage Site’s tentative list.</p>
                <p>Apart from the unique architecture and terracotta craft, Bishnupur  is also famous for its and Baluchari saris made of tussar silk.Baluchari is a gorgeous tradition of handmade fabric with depiction of mythological scenes on the border and pallu of the sari. In the 18th century the Muslim ruler of Bengal, Nawab Murshid Kuli Khan patronized this rich weaving tradition and brought it from Dacca to Baluchar village in Murshidabadh, the then capital of Bengal. But after a devastating flood the weavers moved to Bishnupur and it became under the patronage of the Malla rulers. </p>
                <p>
                    A simple Baluchari has silk threads in monochrome to weave the entire pattern, while others have two or more colours with meenakari work to brighten the patterns. The most gorgeous baluchuries have gold or silver threads that illuminate the patterns to a much extent, these ones are called Swarnachari saris. With changing demand in fashion industry, the same tradition is now passed on to scarves, dresses, handbags and more.
                </p>
                <p>Other minor crafts of no less skill are also present in Bishnupur. Amongst them the Dasavatar playing cards and conch and other vegetable shell carving are noteworthy.</p>
                <p>A unique example of Bengal’s folk art is Bishnupur’s Dasavatar cards made by the Faujdar family. Dasavatar or the ten incarnations of Lord Vishnu, the Hindu deity is painted on playing cards. Made with cloth, natural glue from tamarind seeds and smoothed with stone. These round cards are painted with vegetable dye.</p>
