                <h4>Burdwan crafts tour</h4>
                <p><strong>Burdwan</strong></p>
                <p>Burdwan was once recorded as the richest tract in Bengal and the area of its oldest and most settled cultivation. Burdwan was founded in 1657 by Sangam Rai, of a Hindu Khatri family of Kotli in Lahore, Punjab, whose descendants served in turn the Mughal Emperors and the British government.</p>
                <p>A series of rulers enriched the cultural heritage of the region patronising craft, education and architecture.</p>
                <p>Reputed for its beautiful terracotta temples, Burdwan is made more famous for its Dokra and woodcarving craft. It is also home to small hamlets where the womenfolk are engaged in making beautiful indigenous Bengal embroidery called Kantha on silk and cotton fabric.  </p>
                <p><strong>Dokra </strong> is one of the earliest methods of non-ferrous metal casting known to human civilization. It is the most complicated metal casting done with the lost-wax technique. The technique has managed to survive many centuries and change of dynasties owing to its modesty of application in everyday lives of ordinary people. Mostly drawn from folk culture, the specialty of Dokra metal craft is that each item is exclusive and making its exact replica is nearly impossible. </p>
                <p>A visit to the Dariyapur Dokra tribal village is captivating with the rustic and pastoral charm of this art with its primeval simplicity and beguiling folk motifs. The art is very ethnic and boasts of real folk essence. A local expert will take one through the step-by-step process of creating Dokra artefacts making and one will learn why each piece is unique and making an exact copy is practically impossible . </p>
                <div class="blankdivider30"></div>
                <p><strong>Natungram</strong>, in the district of Burdwan is a small rustic village full of rural and pastoral charm and great artistry. It is the hub of Wooden Doll making, an age old tradition of the Bhaskar, meaning sculptor or Sutradhar, meaning story teller communities that has been continuing through generations and is still alive among 70 odd families of this village. </p>
                <p><strong>Kantha</strong> means ‘rags’ in Sanskrit. It is predominantly the most popular form of embroidery practiced by the rural women of Bengal. Originally Kantha embroidery was made up of discarded sarees. Threads from the border of the old sarees were drawn out and used as the thread for doing embroidery. The traditional form of Kantha embroidery is done where the entire cloth is covered with running stitches creating beautiful folk motifs, floral motifs, animal and birds figures and geometrical shapes. Themes from day to day activities are also a common subject for the embroidery.</p>
